  eprinttype = {arxiv},
  primaryclass = {astro-ph},
  abstract = {Multi-planet systems are valuable arenas for investigating exoplanet architectures and comparing planetary siblings. TOI-1246 is one such system, with a moderately bright K dwarf (\$\textbackslash rm\{V=11.6,\textasciitilde K=9.9\}\$) and four transiting sub-Neptunes identified by TESS with orbital periods of \$4.31\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm\{d\},\textasciitilde 5.90\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm\{d\},\textasciitilde 18.66\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm\{d\}\$, and \$\textasciitilde 37.92\textasciitilde\textbackslash rm\{d\}\$. We collected 130 radial velocity observations with Keck/HIRES and TNG/HARPS-N to measure planet masses. We refit the 14 sectors of TESS photometry to refine planet radii (\$\textbackslash rm\{2.97 \textbackslash pm 0.06\textasciitilde R\_\textbackslash oplus\},\textbackslash rm\{2.47 \textbackslash pm 0.08\textasciitilde R\_\textbackslash oplus\}, \textbackslash rm\{3.46 \textbackslash pm 0.09\textasciitilde R\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$, \$\textbackslash rm\{3.72 \textbackslash pm 0.16\textasciitilde R\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$), and confirm the four planets. We find that TOI-1246 e is substantially more massive than the three inner planets (\$\textbackslash rm\{8.1 \textbackslash pm 1.1 M\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$, \$\textbackslash rm\{8.8 \textbackslash pm 1.2 M\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$, \$\textbackslash rm\{5.3 \textbackslash pm 1.7 M\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$, \$\textbackslash rm\{14.8 \textbackslash pm 2.3 M\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$). The two outer planets, TOI-1246 d and TOI-1246 e, lie near to the 2:1 resonance (\$\textbackslash rm\{P\_\{e\}/P\_\{d\}=2.03\}\$) and exhibit transit timing variations. TOI-1246 is one of the brightest four-planet systems, making it amenable for continued observations. It is one of only six systems with measured masses and radii for all four transiting planets. The planet densities range from \$\textbackslash rm\{0.70 \textbackslash pm 0.24\}\$ to \$3.21 \textbackslash pm 0.44 \textbackslash rm\{g/cm\^3\}\$, implying a range of bulk and atmospheric compositions. We also report a fifth planet candidate found in the RV data with a minimum mass of 25.6 \$\textbackslash pm\$ 3.6 \$\textbackslash rm\{M\_\textbackslash oplus\}\$. This planet candidate is exterior to TOI-1246 e with a candidate period of 93.8 d, and we discuss the implications if it is confirmed to be planetary in nature.},
